Chapter One
Kolon
Itanian time, 4:30 a.m. Kolen hated waking up so early, especially since he was responsible for rousing the rest of the platoon. He silently got out of bed, put on his combat suit, fastened his assault vest, gathered his belongings from the storage cabinet, and carefully picked up a special small box. He shouldered his rifle and attached his helmet to a small hook on his belt. The helmet was fully equipped with all necessary gear, including a breathing apparatus, goggles, and other essential items. After checking his ammunition pouch, he quietly left the barracks. His boots crunching on the muddy and icy ground made a soft, squeaking sound.
He took a lighter out of his jacket pocket and then pulled out a cigarette from another pocket. After lighting the cigarette, he took a gentle puff and then opened the door. Over the past week, he had to strain his mind to wake up his subordinates. He no longer used the preset alarm clock because half the time it didn't go off, and all that could be heard from the speaker was a faint hiss.
"Time to wake them up?" Kollen turned around and saw Lieutenant Nemec approaching.
"Yes," Kollen replied.
"What method are you planning to use this time?"
Kolon hadn't even had time to answer when the door opened, and Harris, Cress, and a few others hurried out, already dressed and ready.
"Good morning," said Cres.
"What woke you up?" Kollen asked.
"First of all, we really don't want to see what method you're going to use today to wake everyone up. Secondly, the first squad to get up will get priority for breakfast," replied a soldier named Ravi. "You know how terrible that breakfast is."
Kolon said, "You're right, Sergeant Ravik." He reached out and pressed the switch. Immediately, a shrill alarm blared through the barrack. He heard someone shouting loudly inside, accompanied by the sound of frantic footsteps.
"Good heavens, Volturi," Nemici said. "I thought they should have learned by now to get up with you."
"My brothers from basic training did exactly that," Kollen said, pointing at Harris, Cress, and Ravek. "But to be fair, their platoon leader and company commander knew to get up before the soldiers did."
A few seconds later, the other soldiers from the platoon ran out. They were all dressed and ready. Some of the new recruits looked groggy, while others appeared very annoyed.
"Good morning, everyone," Kolon said, bursting with enthusiasm.
"Excuse me for speaking plainly, sir, but why did you wake us up in such a way?" asked a突击队员 (corporal).
"Because those ordinary alarm clocks are just junk. And Daybreak never sleeps in," said Kollen.
"Take your personal belongings," Colonel Korney continued. As a lieutenant and deputy commander of the company, he was responsible for assisting Captain Borys Char, the company commander, in supervising and leading the unit. "We will not be returning. Sergeants and lieutenants, give yourself and your men fifteen minutes to do a final check and take the rations you need for today."
The members of Exodus Company quickly dispersed. They were part of the 2nd Shock Division of the Second Army Group. Before their merger, they had originally been two separate companies, Cohort and Dagger. This was an elite unit, and Colonel Kollen felt a complex mix of emotions about being promoted to the rank of lieutenant, for there were many reasons behind it.
Kolon and the platoon leader of the first row, Nemicz, walked side by side along the brightly lit road at the base, where the lights on both sides were powered by generators. Most of the lights were red, which helped them avoid enemy bombers. To counter them, Daybreak had begun employing "Wild Weasel" tactics both in the air and on the ground.
"A new day, a new mission for the Hell Pioneers," Nimich said dryly. "Where are they going to send us this time?"
"An outlying front base outside Ianalos. We were sent to support the ground attack." Kollen said, taking a puff of his cigarette. He felt a bit resentful toward Cress for getting him hooked on cigarettes, but thinking back on the past year filled with countless battles, he let it go and said nothing.
"What a mess. The front lines are in a tough situation," Nimitch said softly. "All the messages coming out of here are about 'supporting the war effort, aiding the Kurgan front.' Why isn't anyone supporting the Holan front?"
"You're right, brother," Kollen said, flicking the cigarette butt into the mud. "We'll go with the first armored platoon. No need to walk. Captain肖 should be there."
"Captain Xiao let us ride with him?" Nimitch asked, somewhat surprised.
"Yes. To be honest, he isn't as bad as I imagined. I mean, he's not great, but he's not unbearable either."
Kalen raised his thumb and index finger, pressing them against the microphone at his throat, while moving the backpack onto his back. "Exodus, all units, assemble at the West Yard after completing the mission. We'll depart at 05:00 with the first armored platoon."
Every few seconds, he received replies from the squad leaders. When they had first arrived, Harris, Cress, and Ravik were all junior non-commissioned officers. The four of them had been close friends ever since their basic training on Earth. Koron felt like he had known them for a long time, even though it had been less than two years. They were all squad leaders, but since the previous platoon leader had been hit by a Daybreak sniper a week ago and had since retired due to injuries, Cress had been leading the second squad.
When they arrived at the vehicle yard, Kullen and Nimitchi's eyes fell upon approximately eight Chronos main battle tanks and four Stryker armored vehicles. Crew members were running around, making sure their war machines were in proper working order. Kullen quickly spotted Captain Borys Chao among the crowd; he was talking with the commander of the armored platoon. As they approached, Captain Chao glanced at them and came forward to meet them. His usually impassive face showed no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nimitz... Lieutenant Valturi..." he said. Colonel Kollan slowed his pace. Captain肖 looked at Kollan's holstered pistol and then raised his head. "Should the company be ready by now?"
